\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What is your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 My present address is 22 Algers Close, Loughton, Essex.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And your marital status?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Widow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The year of your marriage was ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 1889.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I was born in Renfrewshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In a town or a village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Outside Glasgow. But Renfrewshire is quite old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where is the first house that you lived in that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The first house that I lived in that I can remember is the; house in Renfrewshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old were you when you lived there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The earliest ... I don't know. The earliest memories I have ... I don't know. I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know if you moved around a lot when you were a little girl? Did your family move a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 After my father died, yes, but not before that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not before then; you lived quite statically in Renfrewshire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, because this was near his place of business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you remember just one house until your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, the house he died in. I remember it quite well, because by the time he died I was 6. And I remember that very well, indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That's the one house you remember in your childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And where did you move then, after he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
After he died we stayed in the house for a time and then my mother decided ... there were three young children, 2 younger than me and two much older, and my mother decided that ... or her relatives prevailed upon her - to go up to the Highlands and stay t
here, because they thought she'd be better near her sisters who lived up there, and she went there. They thought she'd be better there, but it was a very unfortunate move because she took us and, of course, I remember very well going in a cab in the early
 
morning, and I remember what I had on, too. A brown satin fur-lined coat. I can remember this quite well, and my little sister had one, too, and she was only 18 months. And I was 6, the oldest of the 3. And I can remember going in a can at 4 o'clock in th
e
 morning and hearing the clop-clop of the horses' hooves on the cobbled pavements. There were all cobbled streets. Not pavements, cobbled streets, and I can remember hearing this, very well. And whether I fell asleep then, or not (laughter) I don't rememb
e
r anything more, not a thing. But we got on a passenger boat, you know, to take us from Glasgow up to the Hebrides, and how long we were on the boat I don't know. I don't remember anything at all about that. But I remember getting to my ... or being in my
 
aunt's house, and she had a fairly large house and there were plenty of room in it, and the sea was quite near us. I remember that. And unfortunately, my mother had everything she possessed in big trunks. She gave all the furniture in the house to people 
to keep for her, you know, and most of them kept it for good. She never saw it again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 
But this didn't matter very much, but while we were at my Aunt's in Stornoway, with all my mother possessed in trunks and things, the house went on fire and my mother lost everything she had, and nothing insured.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So what happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, I was taken away by another aunt, she took me, and friends, you know, took everybody from the house; took my aunt we were staying with and her husband and her family, and I think my grandfather as well lived there. He did, yes, my mother's father.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This house in Stornoway you were talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, yes. There was this big fire and the house was absolutely wrecked. And I went to stay with another aunt and an uncle,
 and he was the sheriff of the town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
In Stornoway. And I can remember quite well walking along the street with my uncle and hearing the echo of the pitter-patter of my little feet on the pavement. I was very tiny. And my mother a
nd the other two went somewhere else, and then my mother got a house of her own, and stayed in it for a time. And she found there was no ... sort of ... industry or there was no way of living there at all ..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In Stornoway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In Stornoway, that it w
as a great mistake, she had made a great mistake to give up her house. However, we left Stornoway and came back to Glasgow and started again at scratch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old were you when you came back to Glasgow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I couldn't tell you. I don't know if we were
 there for ... we might have been there for 2 years. I couldn't tell you. I couldn't, really. But I know that we came back from there, my mother and we 3 children. And at that time in her history there was no such thing as pensions for windows or any welf
a
re whatsoever. Nothing, but what you happened to have saved or what your relatives might give you, or something like that. But there was nothing else. Nothing else. And my mother was a very fine, beautiful woman, and very practical. She could do anything 
with her hands, you know, sewing, and she was very artistic and very gifted. But I remember very little of all that. Very little of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And so did you settle in Glasgow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And did you remain there for the rest of your ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Until I was ... 'till I came to London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In the one house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You moved house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, no, not in the one house, and not in the one place. Glasgow's a big city and it has suburbs, and we stayed in various places. We t
ried this place and that place and the other place, I suppose, really, finding which was the most suitable. And I know that I was there ... Oh, I wasn't there all my life. No, I wasn't. That's not true. I was there 'till I was 12, in Glasgow, and my mothe
r
 took very ill and my elder sister, who was 11 years older than me - I was 12 and she was 23 - she came from London where she lived, and she took us 3 children up to Stornoway to this same aunt that we were with before. I was with the aunt ... one aunt to
o
k me, and another aunt took the other two while my mother was ill; and this was when I was 12 years of age. And I went to school there, to a girls' school called the Seminary. Very, very fine teachers, and a good school, and I was very good runner, good a
t singing and good at sewing. I was quite bright at school. But I was there for 4 years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You stayed in Stornoway for 4 years, with this aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, when I was at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The same aunt that you'd lived with before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. I stayed part of 
the time with her, because she had to leave Stornoway during the time that I was with her to go to Portsmouth, where her daughter lived. And her daughter was very ill, and she had to go and look after her daughter. So they sold the house in Stornoway, and
 I went to lived with the aunt who I stayed with at first, when the house went on fire, and went to school while I was with her. And then I came back to Glasgow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you were 16?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When I was 16, yes, just about that age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your two younger brothers and sisters stay in Stornoway as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, they stayed in Stornoway right on until they finished ... Well, no. My youngest sister, she finished her education in Glasgow; and my younger brother, he finished school in Stornoway and became a s
culptor. And he started with an uncle of mine who was a sculptor and it was this that brought him in to doing that. And I stayed with a friend of ours, a doctor and his wife and their family. I stayed with them because my mother was very ill for a long, l
ong time. And when I was with this doctor and his wife. I used to help their two daughters with their lessons. They were younger than me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This is when you came back to Glasgow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When I came back to Glasgow, yes, I used to help them with their les
sons, and then I went to college and started training as - what I thought I was going to be - a secretary, but I didn't like .... I thought typing wasn't what I wanted at all. This college was run by a chartered accountant and his sons, and I said I wante
d to go in for accountancy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was this full time, this college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And did you have to pay fees to the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, oh, yes. But it was very interesting, because I was the only girl in the accounts class. It was all boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How big was the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I don't know. There was lectures going on in this room and that room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there about 100, or 200, or 300?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I don't think there were as many as 200. I don't think so, because it was fee-paying and I s
uppose for these times it was quite expensive, and it was right in the middle of the best past of Glasgow, in Sauchiehall Street, and most of the girls that I made friends with there, their fathers were all in very good positions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 There were other girls in the school, but none in the accountancy class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I was ... There was lots of girls where I went to, when I went to the training for secretarial work but I only stayed there about ... oh, I should think a couple of months and I switched to the acc
ountancy. And I had learned to type of 9 different machines and clean them by that time. This is all the typewriters that there were, so the college must have been quite big. And I remember that the principal's sons, they were all very tall and very lean,
 and they took different classes, you know, at different times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you manage to get into the accountancy class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, without any difficulty, just switched over. And they told me that a woman accountant would never be required. That was all t
he encouragement I got. They didn't know why I wanted to go in for that at all because it would never be wanted. They didn't know there was going to be a war in 1914 when anybody would be glad to grab me up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Why did you want to go into accountancy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Because I liked it, I liked figures, you see. I was always very fond of figures. I used to be top of the class, always, in mental arithmetic. You know, they took us out into the floor, our teacher - a lady - she took us out into the floor and ask us ho
w many beans make five, or something of the kind, and I was always top of the class there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did the boys think of you in this accountancy class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, they didn't think anything at all about me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 They didn't mind a girl?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think I f
elt more awkward than they did because I'd only been in a girls' school, you see. I'd never been with boys, and I think I felt more awkward with them than they did with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long did you stay there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, for 3 years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 'Till you were 19, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother pay for all this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, no, no, my mother didn't pay for it because I had some money left to me, you see, and this helped with it. But my clothes and everything I suppose ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you live at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I told you, I was living with this doctor and his wife when I was at College. I lived with them all the time. \{BLANK\}
 Girls, we got friendly, there was quite a lot of us and we had a very happy life. We used to go in and have lunch, you know, in one of the restaurants in the town, and several of us joined the Women's Social }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 Political Union, that at the time that the suffragettes were beginning to be heard and this was a non-militant branch of it. And I was sent off with some of the other girls who were se
nt off, to do slum work, working the slums of Glasgow, and there were mostly Irish people that had landed in Glasgow, and the slept just as the Indians and the Pakistanis do here, now, 8 and 9 and 10 in one room. They did that at that time, and I was horr
ified because I'd never seen that side of life. However, I got tremendously interested, and interested in politics and my interest in politics has kept from that day to this, and I've never changed them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This started when you were at the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At the college, yes. I've never changed them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What happened after you left the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, I got a job, and a handsome salary. Of course, in Scotland, I will say this, that women had a better opportunity and better educational facilities tha
n they had in England. Women were employed in warehouses and shops, and as clerks and clerkesses and all sorts of things that they weren't employed doing in England. It was only, really, I should think about 1912 or thereabouts that you'd find a shop girl
. They were all shop men. There was no women serving in shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
In England. They started in Scotland before they did in England, and they had better educational facilities. As a matter of fact the ordinary school education - I forget w
hat they call it, School Board Education, or whatever it was - was much higher than the standard in England, and this has been the case until a few years ago and England has come up to Scotland and Scotland has come down to England, if you can understand 
w
hat I mean, educationally. They're more or less on the same line now. But Scotland had St. Andrews University in the year 1300, one of the oldest universities in the country. And very high scholastic achievements, even in villages in the Highlands. The mi
n
ister or somebody like that would teach the boys and people that wanted to learn to read, write and do arithmetic. That was all the education that was required in those days; and some geography and history, telling them about different parts of the world.
 The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 Scots}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 were great pioneers in venturing out into the world across the seas. You see, it was swept by ... Scotland, of course, had the Atlantic Ocean and the North Sea round it and most of the people ... a tremendous number of Scotsmen went abroad in the
 very early days, and especially from the Highlands of Scotland. And the very first settlers in New Zealand in the year 1775 came from Sutherlandshire, and there was nobody there but the Maoris in New Zealand at that time. Cook went 3 times with 3 shiploa
d
s. The first time he went he gave them some roots, vegetable roots and took some cattle out on the ship to them so that they could breed and have food. But they ate the roots and they ate the meat, and they didn't do anything with it except use it for the
m
selves. And the next time he went back a couple of years later he found what they had done, and he took other things to them and the people, our own people, the people from the North of Scotland had gone there quite a number of them, and they were the fir
st settlers in New Zealand. And they were turfed off the land in Scotland, from their own crofts by a man called Sellers. They called him Butcher Sellers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And they were the first ones, as you say that allowed women to ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, they had women working for them because when I came to London to work ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Which was when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, I came to London in 1911 and I didn't stay very long and I went back, because I was only on holiday and I had a good holiday here and saw everything at the Franco-Br
itish Exhibition in London. I went to St. Paul's, St. Margaret's. The House of Commons, The House of Lords, I went everywhere. The Tower of London, I don't know where I didn't go. I went everywhere. And it was the most sweltering summer that I ever knew i
n
 my life. Do you know, walking down Cheapside I had thin kid boots on. It was boots we had, no shoes in these days, and the heat was wearing the soles of my feet. I had a white silk dress on and I remember a very bid hat, and I quite well remember walking
 
and thinking that there was a furnace under my feet. It was so hot. But then, when I came back to London for good, I came back to London in 1913, early 1913. I came back then, but I'd been working in Glasgow in the meantime. I'd been in business in Glasgo
w. But I'll tell you that even after all the studying I did, and everything else, I got a job in one of the best jewelers in Glasgow to keep their stock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was when you first left the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was your first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 First job, and the handsome salary of 10/- a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Good gracious! Ten shillings? And you were keeping the stock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Everything that was sold in the shop I had to mark off every day in a book, a stock book and everything that was bought in, every invoice, ha
d to go through my hands and be put in this, and I had to do ... keep the private ledger as well, for ten shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you come to get this job? Was this the sort of job a man would normally have had? Or did women do that kind of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, they had women ... they had a woman saleswoman in the shop and they had men salesmen, as well, at that time in 1910, they had women saleswomen in shops. But in London here you didn't find any women working in offices or doing anything like that, a
nd banks, or anything of that description.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you come to get this job in Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, there was lots of other people getting jobs as well as me. All the girls that were in my college were all going into offices. Girls were employed at that time in Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 It was particularly accountancy where they felt that you wouldn't be able to use your ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That's what they ... what it was. They said that a woman would never be required to do a profit and l
oss account or a balance sheet. And that was drummed into me from morning 'till night the whole time I was at the college. And still I persevered and nothing would put me off it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did you do after that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Then I went to keep a set of books, all the books at a very high class gentleman's tailor's in Glasgow, and then I came to London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 For good, or for the holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, for good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was in 1913?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 1913.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Before we come on to London can we just go back a little bit. You had two older brothers and sisters, is that it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. One older brother and one older sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Your sister was ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Eleven years older than me and my brother was 6 years older than me, and I had very little contact with them after my fa
ther died. Well, not I ... what I mean, they went to different occupations, but I mean we were all friendly. We were a very happy family, really, but owing to my mother's illness we had to ... They ... my sister was in London working and my elder brother,
 he was working in Glasgow. And my younger brother, he didn't start working until about 1907 or '08, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You had a younger brother and a younger sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Your brother was 18 months when you were 6?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, my sister was 18 months when I was 6. I could tell you a funny story about her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, in these days you hear so much about sex and you hear all the children know everything that's going on in the sex world. I was in my bed one night in our own house when I was 4 years old, I should think. I'd be just about 3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
. And I thought I heard a cat and I got up and went into my mother's room and said 'there's a cat in the house'. And my mother said to me - and I was surprised, at four o'clock in the morning ever
ything seemed very bright. I didn't know 4 o'clock from 6 o'clock, I didn't know the time, even. But she said to me, 'oh, it's not a cat. Look in there', and I looked into a lovely wooden cradle and I saw the most lovely little baby I thought I'd ever see
n
 in the world. It was the loveliest baby 'cos I'd never seen a baby before. Oh, I thought I could eat her, she was so lovely. And I said to my mother 'where has the baby come from?', and my mother said Dr. Hope brought her'. That was our doctor, and he wa
s
 a six-footer with a silk hat on, I remember him quite well, 'in his little black bag'. And I said, 'where did Dr. Hope get her?' and my mother thought for a moment and she said, 'You know these big red and green bottles in the doctor's window' (there's n
o
 chemist shops, there wasn't at that time in Scotland, it was all doctor shops), and I said 'yes', 'well, she came out of one of these bottles'. And I never asked any more questions about where babies came from, but I never passed a doctor's shop without 
p
utting my nose against the glass watching the babies swimming in this red and green water (laughter). Now, this has a very funny sequel to the story; years afterwards (as I told you, my younger sister she was 5 years younger than I was so I would be about
 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 or 3, something like that when I heard this, but I never forgot it. And always, as I said, I couldn't bear to pass a doctor's shop without looking at the babies in the glass) and a number of years later - I never again asked my mother where the babie
s came from nor anything about babies, it didn't interest me - and one nice summer's day, I remember very well, I had on a very pretty frock with puffed yellow sleeves and velvet yoke, velvet sleeves and yoke that my mother had made for me, and she sent m
e
 down the stairs to the greengrocer's shop with a large basket to get vegetables for her - I would be about 10 at that time, I think, or somewhere ... yes, I'd be about ten - to go down to the green - grocer's and get some vegetables for her. And I went w
i
th this market basket, one of these baskets that open up like that, and to go to the greengrocer's I had to pass a doctor's shop. And when I came to the doctor's shop I saw a long lot of people waiting to go in to the doctor's shop, what you would call a 
q
ueue today, and I thought 'I must stand in the queue, too'. So I stood in the queue and I thought they were all waiting for babies 'and I'm going to bring a baby home to my mother and put it in the basket'. And I remember very well wondering whether it wo
u
ld have blue eyes or black eyes and would it be a boy or a girl, and how would I get it into the basket. Well, in any case, I suppose I must have been standing there a long time because my mother was very worried about me and had no idea where I'd got to.
 
And I eventually got into the doctor's shop and what happened in the doctor's shop I don't know, but I came home minus a sleeve and I was crying, and no vegetables. I had been vaccinated for smallpox! (laughter) That's true. This would be about 1899, ther
e
 was an epidemic of smallpox in Glasgow, and you can see the mark on my arm to this day. Not in my day, there wasn't such a thing. You were told what was right and what was wrong and that was all that you knew about it. And our lives were very different t
o what they are today, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
How did people cope with getting married, then? What did people feel getting married was or what it was about? Was this often a shock for girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I suppose it might have been, but that would be depending on 
themselves and the man they married, I suppose, really. But I do think, myself, that they had no sort of ... no earthly idea of what our bodies were ... how they were made, or anything else. I know this, that when I was expecting my first baby I didn't kn
ow whether it was going to come out of my tummy or where it was going to come out. And this is perfectly true, and I was 27}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you weren't unusual, presumably? This was the same for everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, I think this was ... Sex was never dis
cussed, this was a sacred thing between a husband and wife and nobody ... you wouldn't even tell your mother or anybody belonging to you anything that happened within your bedroom. Never! It was very sacred to you. And nice men - I don't know, there might
 
have been lots of ... as much vice in the world, I suppose, always. There's always been vice in the world, but I don't think it was quite so common. Perhaps in the earlier ages it might have been, you know, a hundred or 150 years before it might have been
.
 I think people were very brutal in their ... a couple of centuries ago. I think there was more brutality and roughness. And then as people became ... better educated, I suppose, or came from families that were well educated - because there was education 
i
n Scotland way back in 1500, the year 1500, and the wealthy people sent their daughters and their sons to Lausanne and Paris and different places in France to finish their education. And they did that from the Highlands of Scotland. And the same way in Gl
a
sgow and Edinburgh and Dundee and Aberdeen, Perth, and all these places, Inverness, they all ... there was a fair number, I should think quite a large number of fairly well-to-do people, because it was nothing to see in Glasgow, I remember very well seein
g
 beautiful carriages-and-pairs and the footmen at the front of the carriage going along, you know, the main streets of Glasgow, and some very large houses with huge households. Of course, they had that in England, too. But that was quite common throughout
 the whole of Great Britain, just great Britain. That was the whole of Great Britain at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That is interesting. That's a lovely story, anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 But cut that out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, they'll love to hear that. So you had one sister who was 4 years younger than you and a brother who was younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, my sister was 5 years younger than me and my brother was 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  years younger than me. And a brother 6 years older and a sister 11 years older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So your mother had 5 children altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have any other children who didn't live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. I think we had a sister that was older than me, I think she was between my elder brother and my elder sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any children between you and your brother? There was 6 years between you and your brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think so. I don't know. I don't know. As I told you, everything that went on in your parents' bedroom we knew nothing about.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, he was 42 when he died and I was 6, so that makes him 36.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He came from the Island of Lewis in the Outer Hebrides, a place called Ness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What was his occupation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He was a brilliant engineer. He started in the firm that he was with when he was 16, and remained with them 'till he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He just had this one job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 One job only. He became manager of the engineering section of this particular firm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What sort of engineering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Ships. Building ships' engines, there's not a ship
 that sailed on the sea that didn't have Stephen's engines in it. Stephens Shipbuilders at House in Glasgow. And my father was there all his life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And he became the manager of the ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Of that section, the engineering section.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was he ever out of work that you know of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I don't know. Oh, well, now, wait a minute 'till I see if I can work this out. Well, I don't know how old my mother was when she was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old was she when she died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 She was 83, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And what year did she died in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 She died in 1931. Now in 1931 I'd be 32, would I?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 42.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 42? Not as much as that. Yes, that's quite right. Well, now, my mother would be about 42 when I was bor
n. That would be about it. I don't think she was as old as that, she couldn't be. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 
She couldn't be as old as that, because my brother and my sister came after me, and she was younger than my father. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think my mother was about 36 when I was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 About the same as your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
She came from the Island of Harris. There's Lewes and Harris, they're joined, but there's one island called The Long Island in the most northerly part of the Western Isles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Both of them from the Hebrides, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Both of them Hebridean, and my mother's blood goes back for 400 years. Nothing but Highland blood in my veins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did your father come to be in Glasgow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He came to serve his apprenticeship as an engineer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At this firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When he was 16?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When he was 16.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would he have worked before the age of 16?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, no. He might have been 15 when he came, I couldn't tell you. 15 or 16 and he had been all his life with the same firm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Had your mother any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she work after she was married, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You worked in a tailor's until you left Glasgow in 1913?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 High class tailor's, gentleman's tailor's, as a bookkeeper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And then you came to London. What made you come to London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Because I had been very ill. I developed glands and I was for 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  years and had 13 operations on my neck by Sir John Barlow in Glasgow for glands, and I had just started to
 put my foot on the ladder of the best job in the whole of Scotland. I started with the Commission for National Health that Lloyd George brought in in 1911. I got a wonderful post because of my qualifications and it had to ... The Civil Service - although
 
I had letters from my doctor to say this was neither infectious or contagious - there was 500 women working in this office to do the whole of ... from Newcastle up to the whole of Scotland, the whole of the Western Region, for the National Health Service 
when it began in 1911. And when this lump came I thought it was mumps, but it wasn't mumps. It turned out to be tubercular glands, and you can see all the scars I've got if you look into my neck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And I've never noticed!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Is that so? And I was very
 conscious of them, all up here and the back of my neck. The doctors told me eventually that I must go to a more relaxing climate. I'd always been very energetic and slept very badly, I'd always suffered with insomnia. I do now, I've suffered with it all 
m
y life. But the doctors said I must go to a more relaxing climate, could I go to England because Scotland was too bracing for me and these glands would not heal up, and they thought that if I came to England that it would be better for me. So I said I cou
ld come to London, and I did come to London. And they persisted for a time but not as bad as they were. But even after my children were born I had some more of them, and then they died out altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So this is how you came to be in London, because of your health?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
This is what brought me to London, and there's a very true saying, that all things work together for our good. And there's no doubt about it that my coming to London worked for the whole of my life, all the good in my life. I met my hus
band in London in my sister's house; I got a good job in London; I've had a very happy life here, full of interest, full of everything worth - while ; scope for going to concerts, hearing the greatest singers in the Albert Hall that you could wish to hear
. All these things came to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you were glad you came to London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, I wouldn't go back ... I wouldn't live anywhere else in the world! I love London, I wouldn't live anywhere else in the world, not from choice. But that was what brought me to London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you came to your sister. This is your sister that was 11 years older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, and I stayed with her, and then I went to work and I got this job with the accountants and they were very ... my boss told me that I was the first woman auditor to be employed in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you tell me about this job? What job was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Being an auditor, an accountant, with a firm of Chartered Accountants in London, the second biggest firm in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you come to get this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I suppose through the paper. It was the only medium, there wasn't bureau then. There was nothing like that. That could have been the only medium that I could have got it through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you saw a job advertised and you just applied?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, I su
ppose so. And I have the offer of ... while I was with them during the War, an Australian agricultural company, I was doing one of their audits, and they offered me the chief accountant's job at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 \'a3}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 500 a year, but I didn't take it. They said they would ask m
y firm to second me to them, but I said 'no' because I had by this time, I had got or was just about to get engaged to my husband and I knew that it wouldn't be fair to them if I took on another job. And I had a five-year contract with my own firm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you joined this firm you had to sign a contract for 5 years, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not at first, but I did later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you remember your interview for this job? Was there any surprise that a woman answered? Was there any reluctance to employ a woman?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, they were only too glad to get me. They were only too glad to get me because they hadn't got people here that could do this sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was 1913?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 1913, yes. They had nobody here that could ... No, it wasn't 1913. It was after the Wa
r in 1914, after the War broke out in 1914 that I got this job. I was ill when I came here, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I see, so you didn't work at first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At first, no. At first I didn't, but then I looked for a job, and I got a job before that. Now, let me thin
k. I got a job as a bookkeeper. Yes, that's quite right. I did get a job as a bookkeeper with a firm of ... dear me, what were they? Oh, stores. They sold clothing, and I was with them for about 6 months, or 7 months, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did your sister live?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I'd now like to ask you about life at home when you were a child. You lived in Renfrewshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you remember how many rooms there were in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, five or 6, anyway, there was all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Downstairs what rooms would there be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 It was all on the level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I see, all on a level. Did you have the whole house to yourself ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Or did anyone else live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were your older sister and brother still there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, my family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have anybody else living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 We had a general servant and a washerwoman that came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You had a general servant, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, we had a general servant, lived in the house, slept in. She had a very small room off the kitchen, I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Maybe I could ask you just a few questions about her. She had a cap and an apron, you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 White cap and an apron, I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she look after you children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think she did everything and anything. My mother was very good, and I think she did everything that was required of her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did she call you, or what did you call her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I was always called Missie Mary, and I don't remember her name, even. I've a feeling it was Kate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she eat with the family at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. No, no. She had her food in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have the same food as you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have time off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes! She used to have an evening off, I think. I think th
ey all had some time off, and Sunday part of the day to go to the Church. And I remember my father standing with his silk hat on ready to go to the church waiting for someone to go with him. I can remember that quite well, seeing him there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Going with the maid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, going with the family, my mother or somebody, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Maids, in those days, were they kept in the kitchen, and was it their job to look after the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Help generally. Help generally. They kept things clean and they d
id the scrubbing and they helped ... did the vegetables and they helped with the cooking when necessary, and helped with the children when necessary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Just did anything that was necessary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Anything at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have any sort of relationship with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they feel that they should give her any moral guidance or training or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I think they always had to have references, and they were very ... according to today's standards they were very poorly
 paid because they only got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 6 a year, I think, and their food and their uniform. But she had a good home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have much contact with you? Did she ever take you children out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, she used to take us to the park quite near by for walks a
nd I can tell you a funny incident about that, too, because at some time or other I must have slipped away from her and I got locked in the park, picking pansies, if you please, which I wasn't supposed to touch. And I don't know how long I'd been in the p
ark, but the park was closed and I was locked in. But eventually I found a gate and I stood there and somebody saw me at the gate and they must have ... I don't know who they went for, or what happened, but I was restored to my family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did this girl get into trouble for losing you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, no. I don't think so. It was me that got into trouble! (laughter) for getting lost. I don't think I got into trouble really, because I was too small to get into any trouble. It was later on I got trouble. I got thra
shings for my naughtiness, or put to bed and no supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And she were a white apron and cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And a black dress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In the afternoons she wore a black dress, but in the mornings she wore a striped sort of cotton frock, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would she have to ever bath you and put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. No, she didn't do that, unless on an extraordinary occasion she might.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she wait at table at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, she used to bring in the food. But we never had our food with our
 father and mother, except on Saturdays and Sundays, I think. I can't remember anything about a middle of the day meal. I can't remember sitting at the table except at breakfast time in the morning, because we were put to bed very early, about 6 o'clock a
t night, and we got our tea by ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did this girl stay with you until you moved from the house in Renfrewshire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I don't think so, because I think when my father had his accident, he came home from hospital and the whole house was altere
d round and in the front room a bed was put specially near the window for my father, so that he might see what was going on outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was that a sort of a parlour, that front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, it would be called that. That's what it would be, something
 like that. But that was the room where we had a great big oval mahogany table and I very well remember a horrible experience I had. When my mother was having friends to tea - there was 2 rooms that she used - she was having friends to tea and I was put i
nto this room with the big table, and a great big mirror over the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 mantelpiece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
, a gilt mirror, and I was given some sort of magazine with pictures and a pair of scissors to cut out and be a good girl until my mother came and released me - children were suppo
sed to be seen and not heard, in these days, and when your mother was having her friends to afternoon tea you weren't allowed to be listening. Well, I was in this room and I had the scissors and I did cutting-out for a while, and then I thought }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 I'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  like to
 get up on the table and I got up on the table and stood in the middle with the scissors in my hand and cut one side of my hair off. So you can imagine that I got a nice thrashing, and I was taken to the barber the next day and told that I would never be 
allowed to have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3605241\charrsid4213195  long}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 hair any more, and neither did I 'till I was over 16 ... 'till I was about 15 my hair was never allowed to grow. It was cut short like a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I suppose I was in tears, I don't know, but I just
 remember seeing myself looking very funny with one side of my hair on and the other with hair off. (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This is before you were 6?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, long before I was 6, yes. Must have been a year before that. Must have been before I was 5 because my f
ather occupied that room at the time when he was ill, so that would make me less than 5. But I remember having the magazine and the scissors, I was quite happy sitting cutting out on the table and all of a sudden what made me get up to look at myself in t
he mirror, I don't know. It was a huge mirror, gilt. And I looked at myself and I thought I'll just trim my hair, and then I started and I trimmed it all away on one side, and I couldn't do anything with the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You said that you had a washerwoman as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
She used to come in 2 days, I think it was on Mondays and Tuesdays. Two days, I can't tell you. She used to come in and I remember the great big tubs because they were taller, ... the tubs were bigger than me, you know, they were big wooden t
ubs. And there was a wash house, a wash house almost in every one of these ... that sort of cottage type of house - and a boiler for boiling the clothes, that was there. But I remember the big tubs and I can remember the smell of the parazone used to blea
ching to this day. And I use Parazone for bleaching, always, after all these years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And she ironed it all as well, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, she used to come in and wash and iron. Do the washing and the ironing. And there was various people used to come
 to the door, there was lots of beggars in these days, I remember. And I remember my mother being very cross because she ... she would be very kind to people like that and she would ask Kate to let them have a cup of soup. It was a bowl of soup, there was
 
no cups then, a bowl of soup. And when they came early in the morning she would ask that they be given a bowl of porridge. And one of these wretched beggars tipped the porridge out and put it under the mat at the door and whoever went out first slipped an
d
 fell. I don't know who went out first, but somebody slipped and fell. But it shows that even in these days the beggars were sometimes ungrateful for what they got. But of course, values are very different to what they are today. You know, the price of fo
o
d ... In Scotland, you know, it's more like that still to this day. They never buy potatoes by the lb., they buy them by the stone, and the same with flour, 112 lbs. of flour at a time, in a big bin, one side for flour and the other side for oatmeal. And 
everything was very cheap, indeed, Vegetables, you would get ... for 2 pennies you would get carrots, onions, turnips, cabbage, or a leek and cabbage and a bit of parsley, all for 2d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So food was plentiful. To go back to the girl that was living with you, you started saying that she left ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
After my father took ill, because, as I said, we had to have another room for him by himself. He had to have a room of his own and he went into the front room and lay there until he died, and I remember him dying quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she have a room to herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Before that, yes, that's why she had to go because we hadn't got enough room, to give her an extra room. My mother had to have her room.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother or father make or mend your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 My mother mended our clothes, but not my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she make them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, she did, and she made them very nicely, too. She used to make frocks. Everybody used to do that, or else have a sewing woman come in and help with it. They had that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You said that you remember vividly wearing aprons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Pinafores.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she make those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I'm sure she did. Oh, yes, I'm sure she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And what about for the boys, would she make the boys' clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, and I myself, when my son
 was a little boy of 3 I made his first pair of trousers and little top, and I did that until he was about 9, and then took him to D.H. Evans and got him fitted out there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they ever buy clothes as well as make them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, because I had a sailor's suit when I was about 4 or 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
, with a little sailor collar, blue, and a hat, and I remember them putting me on a table to look at it to see if it was all right and I suppose I passed muster. But how long I passed muster I wouldn't like to say (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When did you have new clothes, at any special time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, no. When I was young people didn't have, like, Bank holidays. I don't remember anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where would you have gone to buy clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, in a clothes shop,
 there was quite some ... very big shops in Glasgow. And I know that my mother was always beautifully dressed, and she used to wear a black dress and a little white collar on it, and she always used to talk about matelasse silk whatever that is, I don't k
now. Some sort of silk. But she always was very well dressed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever have secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What about shoes, did your father make or mend your shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you say earlier that you wore boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Alway
s. Everybody wore boots, there was no such a thing as shoes for either man, woman or child until about 19 ..... I should think about 1913 or thereabouts. There wasn't such a thing. It was after the First World War, during the First World War, I think, tha
t shoes became fashionable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he do any decorating or repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Light any fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. Not that I know of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he dress you or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Might tell us stories, perhaps, on a Sunday or some time like that. But I used to go and meet him every night and I had a clean pinafore put on me, to go to the corner which was two or 3 steps away, and he
'd carry me home on his shoulder and this was a great experience.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he ever look after you when she was out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, she never went out without him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think you said earlier that this ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, about 6 o'clock you were put to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, as a rule.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I suppose when I was about 8 or 9 or so, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 With my little sister, ultimately.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Had your older sister left home by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. Yes, she had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
We had a tub, a bath tub in a room. There was nothing else in it, but just the bath tub. It was off a room, you know, like a room with a little bit off it and there was this bath tub in there, and the water had to be carried in a hot-can of water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you had a special room just for bathing in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, not only for bathing in, but you were allowed to play in it and do various things like that, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And then, did you have a kitchen, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And a scullery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, I don't remember any scullery. Although, yes, I think there was a scullery now I come to think of it. Yes, there was, with 2 steps down. That's right, I remember now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How many bedrooms can you remember, before your father was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think there was 3. There must have been 3 bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I think we were thrown in to this tub of water every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I should think nearly every day in the week, for they were always filthy by the time we had played about in them for a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In this room where I told you I cut my hair. It was a round table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any occasions when the family ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not that I know of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When she cooked, she cooked in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 On a range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A range. That had a little fire underneath the oven. 
In these days there was only gas burners in the house, there was no incandescent light, even. Open burners, and you had what they called a chandelier and that had globes and these were in the best rooms, but in the ordinary rooms there was just a light co
ming out of the wall, a wall bracket with a light to it and that was gas. And most of the cooking was done on coal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you say just now that you can't remember having meals, much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, because you see, I was too small. I suppose I'd be in bed by the time my father came home. But I do remember a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 Halloween}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 party and I was allowed to stay up, and I remember seeing a barrel of apples at one side of the fire and a great big brown bag full of nuts on the other, and I don't remember anything more about i
t except ducking for apples, you know, my sister and a friend of hers and other two friends came, they all came in for this apple ducking. And you knelt on a chair and had a fork in your mouth and you dropped the fork to try and hit an apple, and it was q
uite a business and great fun. Some people were very skilful at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was for adults, mainly, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, yes. No small child could ever do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You were allowed to stay up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I was allowed to look on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Normally you ate your meals separately from your parents, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, no, no, but the only times I think that we all sat down together would be on a Sunday, when my father came home from Church. And he would do the carving, and we sat together then, but I think ... I do
n't think he came home in the middle of the day, I can't remember. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have breakfast all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, because my father went away early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did you usually eat and drink for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Porridge, that I ha
ted and as soon as my mother's back was turned if I could get the opportunity I would throw it up the chimneypot (laughter) so that I didn't have to eat it. I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 hated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  porridge!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You threw it up the chimney?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Up the chimney. I don't know where it we
nt after that (laughter). I just know that if I couldn't ... if my brother wasn't looking I'd put it on his plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they like porridge, your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't know, I suppose my brother used to eat it because I remember, there was
 porridge and milk, always, and sometimes you had a boiled egg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have anything different on certain days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, nothing like that. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A proper meal, I can't remember very much, but vegetable soup, there wa
s always soup in every Scottish house, there was always soup or broth of some description, made with real stock, with the bones put on the side of the fire and allowed to simmer there. And then, barley and vegetables; different kinds of soup for different
 occasions. But I loved ... to this day I make soup every ... in the wintertime I make soup two or 3 times a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You make your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, I make my own soup.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have anything different for lunch on Sundays when your father was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I think it would be probably a bigger lunch, I don't know. I think it would be a bigger lunch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And in the afternoon or evening, what meal did you have then, what was that called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, we used to have our tea, Scottish people had high
 tea, you know, fried fish and bread and butter and cakes and scones and things like that. They make a very nice table, Scottish people do, for high tea. Fish, or boiled bacon and salad or something like that. They didn't have many salads. I remember seei
ng the first tomato that I ever saw in my life and I thought it was an apple, a kind of apple, and I went in and bought one and I was so disgusted with the taste that I nearly went back and threw it at the woman in the shop (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was this in Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, when I was about 7 or 8 or something, 9. You know, instead of going to the sweet shop to buy a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 penn'orth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  of sweets I went in and bought, I suppose, a ld. tomato, not knowing what it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother or father bake bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 My m
other baked beautifully, bread and scones, and always made her own jam, and so do I, to this day. I've never bought a pot of jam during my married life. I make all my own marmalade and I do it to this day. I cut the oranges up and make my own marmalade. 2
6
 or 40 lbs. when I used to have my family at home. I have strawberry jam, I've blackcurrant jam, I've got everything in my jam cupboard, and I can open a pot of jam any time I want, and it's all homemade. And I bottle all my own fruit and I make all my ow
n chutney.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother do that as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, I can't tell you that. I couldn't tell you that because I know this: that fruit and vegetables were very limited in Scotland. You got oranges and apples, I can remember those, but I don't remember any other fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother make pickles or wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think she ever made wine and I don't know if she ever made pickles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What about medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, the doctor was always sent for, Dr. Hope, our doctor. He was always sent for if there was anything wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, not that I know of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your parents grow their own vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you remember tinned or dried vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you keep any livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Hens, or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How many times a week do you think you ate meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I should think every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Ever tinned meat, that you know of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever get any extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, not from poaching. We might have bought rabbit, my mother probably bought rabbits, but ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you remember seeing your mother have less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You wouldn't know if your father had more, would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I'm sure he would have more, probably need to have a big meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would you be allowed to talk during meals, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Depending on how loud you talked. If you were eating your food, sometimes if you were laughing and giggling your mother wo
uld tell you to be quiet and get on with your meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. Oh, yes, and you were expected to say 'please' and 'thank you'. And you always had a bib put on you to keep you clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Could you ask to have things passed to you, or did you have to wait 'till it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have to eat everything that was on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, you were asked to, but sometimes the chimney was very handy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Everything went up the chimney?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 (laughter) Porridge, particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What would your parents' attitude have been if you'd left it on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, my mother's attitude would be 'if you don't take it now you'll get it for your dinner'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes. Oh, yes, definitely. That's why it went up the chimney, or on to my brother's plate. And not only what would happen up that chimney, but what would have happened to me if my mother had caught me doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Could you bring toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I don't think so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Or a book?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You were supposed to sit until everybody was finished, then leave the table, or beg to be excused.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you always sit in the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother serve the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Easy? Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was she an affectionate sort of mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. Oh, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If you had any worries could you share them with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I never knew what a worry was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What about your father? You said you used to run to meet him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, and he'd carry me home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you particularly close to him, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not any more s
o ... My little brother used to come, too, one on each shoulder. Oh, no, there was no divided affections at all. We were a happy family, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you moved to Stornoway you were away from your mother for quite a long time., when you were 12, I'm talking about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When she was ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You were away from her for quite a long time, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, 12 'till I was about 15. Three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you see much of her during that period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, not at all. Not at all, oh, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When did you go back to live with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 As a matter of fact she lived with my sister that was married after she got better and I stayed with my sister, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, this was in Glasgow, after ... My sister had lived in L
ondon before that and then she got married and came back to live in Glasgow and my mother lived with my sister, and I came and lived with my sister, too, for a time. A short time. And then these friends of ours that I told you, a doctor and his wife and t
heir 2 daughters, they thought it would be nice for me to be with their 2 girls and I went and stayed with them, and I went to college from them, as I told you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you live much with your younger brother and sister? Were you with them for much of your upbringing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, not so very much because they were still up in the Highlands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I see, they stayed with your aunt and uncle up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. Well, when they came back, of course, we all congregated together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know what kind of person your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What their expectations for you, or hopes for you, were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I don't think people went into that when I was young, not at all. All the things you were taught to do, what was right and what was wrong, and s
ay your prayers at night and when you were a little older go to Sunday School. I don't think that people ever sort of ... mapped out the lives of their children. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you think this is different now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, I don't know now. I
 can't tell you what people do now. Looking at the present generation, of what we see on the television, and things, I wonder .... I don't know what sort of homes they must come from and I'm perfectly sure a lot of them come from very nice homes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What would your mother have thought of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, you weren't allowed to do that. And you weren't allowed to do anything on Sundays, at all. And I well remember my brother, the eldest one was 6 years older than me and the youngest one was 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  years 
younger than me, and I remember my mother sitting in an easy chair asleep on a Sunday afternoon, and my elder brother getting out a pack of cards and a box of matches, and we played Banker, and I played with them and my mother was still sound asleep.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You could only do that because she was asleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, 'cos she was asleep. Oh, this was done very quietly so that she wouldn't hear us at all. And here was I on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3605241\charrsid4213195 Sabbath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3605241\charrsid4213195 D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
ay, doing the worst thing I could do, play cards and gamble with bits of sticks. I suppose ... how old would I be then? Oh, I suppose I'd be 8 or 9, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You said that when she had visitors you children weren't allowed to talk to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. We were allowed to say 'good afternoon' to them and do a little curt
sey sometimes, the girls. We were taught to do this, and then go and play with our things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You weren't expected to join in their conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If something happened that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I didn't really reach the age where my parents could really disapprove of anything that I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, we always got a birthday cake, or something like that, but that was all. T
here was never much fuss made of it. We might get a present. The same as at Christmas time you got ... you hung up your stocking. It wasn't like nowadays where they hang up a pillowcase, or they don't hang up anything at all they just sit waiting for the 
Christmas presents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you think of anything you did do together as a family at Christmas? Can you remember any Christmases?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I remember hanging the stockings at the end of the bed and being told all about Father Christmas when I was younger,
 but then as I said already, I was by myself away from the others for quite a while, so there wasn't all that much ... And in Scotland, you know, Christmas was never held as a holiday, even.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no. No, no. The Church of Scotland, yo
u see, and especially some denominations of the Church, they didn't believe in the New Testament at all. It was all Old Testament they believed in, and Christmas was not a holiday. In the City of Glasgow it was not a holiday at all. All the shops were ope
n just as usual. But now it is. They've changed. Now Christmas is made more of and they use ... buy turkeys or chicken or something like that, but they never used to in the old days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So did you celebrate at all over that period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The New Year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What would happen at New Year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, well, the new year was always celebrated and it was a holiday, and it is a holiday in Scotland yet, and everybody had parties to bring in the new year. You know, at 12 o'clock when the new year's striking you'd al
l get together and join in and sing Auld Lang Syne or something like that. And you'd have nice food to eat, as they do at all parties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would children be allowed to stay up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not when they're little? They wouldn't be. They wouldn't be when they were little, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 But as you got older you would celebrate it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, when you get older you celebrate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you play any musical instruments in your home? Or even when you lived with your aunt and uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, when I lived with my aunt 
I played the piano and I used to sing. And I used to go and sing at the Sunday School parties, and things like that when I was 11 or 12. I had quite a nice voice. And my voice developed and was a very good voice, a mezzo soprano, and I used to sing at lot
s of social evenings in London later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If you had any visitors in, or if your aunt and uncle had any visitors in, would you entertain them by singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, when I was a very small child I remember being pulled out to sing a song, before my
 father died I remember that, when I was a tiny little thing. But they didn't have many parties that I can remember. I can't remember any parties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there books in the homes where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Books, oh, yes, plenty of books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, plenty of books, and not many newspapers. There were very few newspapers, but books there was. There was The Boys' Own Magazine, or something, and The Girls' Own Magazine, or something of the kind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you remember ever being read aloud to by your mother or by your aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
You said earlier on that you could remember your father's funeral, although you didn't fully understand it at the time, can you tell me a little bit about it, what you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I remember my fa
ther's death. I remember that very well because we stood round his bed when he died, and I remember seeing his coffin on the table. I remember that. And then I remember the day when he was being buried, the minister came to the house and there was a servi
c
e in the house, and after the people that were going to the service had gone I lifted the Venetian blinds to look at the cortege going away, and all the men from the shipbuilding yard, the section where my father was, followed in their working clothes, as
 
also did the ... the relatives first, and then the men from the yard, and then the freemasons in their regalia walked behind. And of course, I had never seen a funeral in my life, I didn't know it was a funeral, I didn't know what it was, I just knew that
 ... I didn't realise that my father was really dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there carriages for the ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I don't think there was. If I can remember right there was a hearse, you know, and ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 With horses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 With horses. And there was no ... not like they are in England. In London, when I came to London - may I go off for a moment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
When I came to London I saw a funeral in the Mile End Road or somewhere, and the men ... there was weepers, they were calls weepers, with black crepe on them
. There was nothing like that in Scotland, it was very subdued. Funerals were very subdued indeed. And there was no motorcars, there was cabs. If you had a cab that's what you had, unless you were wealthy enough to have carriages and pairs of your own. Bu
t funerals have always been very somber things in Scotland, and they still are. And women never go to them. Never. A woman }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  goes to a funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Didn't your mother, even, go to ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. No. No. Women don't go to funerals in Scotland. They do n
ow, more, but in the old days a woman never went to a funeral. Just the same as a woman never went into a public house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you taken out visiting friends or neighbours or relatives, ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I don't remember doing anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Sometimes. And I remember standing on ... when my mother went to pay her bills at the grocer's, the grocer putting me up on the counter and asking me to sing a song, and he would give me some sweets. And I remember twisting all 
my pinafore up in my hand. But that was when I was about 4.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you remember any outings with your parents at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. I don't think there was such a thing as outings. The only outings I remember was after I was grown up when I came to London an
d then we went outings, different places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not when I was little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How were Saturdays spent when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, you used to get a penny on Saturday and that was the main object of Saturdays, to get your Saturday penny (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you able to put on old clothes and play on Saturdays, or did you have to do anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I think you had the same clothes as you had every other day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 But what about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, Sun
day was ... you weren't allowed to do anything on Sunday except go to Church and have your food, of course. But you weren't allowed to sing, or play a musical instrument, or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No games at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, nothing like that. You weren't allowed out to play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What were you expected to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, you were expected to read your Bible if you were old enough, and if you were just a tiny tot, well, you just played about with your things, your own toys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you wear special clothes? Did you have different clothes on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When we grew older, but not when we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your parents attend a place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. My father and mother both went to Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What denomination?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Presbyterians.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go to Church, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not when I was little, but when I was 12 I went to Church. Eleven, or 12, or 10, something like that, to Sunday School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You went to Sunday School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any Sunday School outings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, they used to have picnics some place or other, and I don't know how ... I can't ever remember how we went, but I remember being on one of these outings. Whether we walked, or what, I don't know. I just don't remember. I'
ve just got a vague idea that there was such a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any social activities organised by the Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not other than the Sunday School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I can't tell you that because I wasn't a youth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever belong to a choir at any of the churches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When I was grown up, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you were grown up but not when you were young. Was Grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Who said Grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 We were all supposed to say Grace, but your father or mother usually did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not as such when I was a child, but always taught to pray.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know now if your father took any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I know now that my father was a Tory, and he was interested in politics but he didn't ... there wasn't the political activity then that there is now. I remember - oh, years after my father died I remember seeing Gladstone in Glasg
ow, and I think really that it was at the time of the Boer War that people got more conscious of politics. And the whole of Scotland was practically Liberal at that time but, alas, they've changed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was your mother ever interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh
, she was interested, I think, from the point of view of once women got a vote she would go and vote, but in those days women had no vote, not 'till 1917, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And she would vote then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she ever work for any particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think so. I don't think she did any work like that at all. Nothing that I know of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When she wasn't doing her work how did she spend her time? Do you know what your parents did?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When she had her home and we were at ho
me there was always sewing, and cooking, and plenty to do. If there was 3 children and herself, there was 4 of us, perhaps more of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you mentioned earlier that she had people to tea. Would these be friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, friends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did any of your relatives live nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not far away I had 2 aunts that used to come in quite often to see us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go to see them much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know anything about your father's activities when he was alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If he played any sports, or if he went to any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, I don't think so. He was very interested in his work. He was very sociable and I think they used to go to social gatherings now and again, he and my mother, but as I said, he died when I was very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know if your mother belonged to any savings clubs, or boot clubs, sick clubs, or funeral clubs, anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know, I don't think there was such a thing as a club. I don't think there was any clubs in my tim
e when I was young. I can't remember any clubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 As a child who did you mainly play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, children of my own age if there was any available, if I was anywhere where they were near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did you play? In gardens, or in the street, or in other people's homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
In gardens, mostly, and sometimes in other people's homes. When I was older, about 12, these are 3 of my friends and we're still friendly, and I've know them since 12 years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This is from Stornoway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In Stornoway, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you remember what games you used to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I know we used to play ball a lot, and rounders, I can remember we played that when I was, you know, a girl.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you used to play mainly ball games? Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I don't think there's a child alive that doesn't get dirty sometimes. You know, you're sure to get your hands dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no. Oh, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you discouraged from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, there wasn't any children near us, really. I don't remember other children near us at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Just the 2 girls you've already mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Ah, but that was after I was 12. Oh, I'd plenty of girlfriends up in Stornoway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Before that, though, did you just play with your brother and sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you were at school did you have any hobbies? Did you keep any pets, or collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think so. I don't think so because when I was at school I was busy learning and ... A certain amount of play, I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go for walks then, or fishing, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I sometimes went for walks during the holidays, and I remember taking my sister on to an island, we went over a cockle strand a
nd the tide came in and we were on the island and we'd to be rescued off it. So no more of the cockle strands for me! (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Running, jumping, climbing, anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go to any theatres or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 There was no theatres and no concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
There was no cinemas. I remember being to a ... phonograph they called them, I think, at my Sunday School, and that was the first sort of thing that I'd ever been to like that, and 
somebody or other who had taken these pictures ... were they pictures? No, I think they were just things coming out of a horn, I can't remember. It was a long time ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What had you used to spend your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 pocket money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, if I had any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 pocket money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  it would go on sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You said that your parents had friends coming in, and they went out, didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did friends call in casually, without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, yes. That's a very great feature of Scottish life, that pe
ople never ... they don't do as you do now, ring up and say 'I'm coming to see you', there was no telephones and people just knocked on your door or rang the bell and they were made very welcome
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And given something to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Whatever time ... yes,
 whatever time they called, if it was mealtimes they would join in the meal, if it was in the afternoon time they would have a cup of tea, or something like that. But Scotland is absolutely noted for that, that ... you know, it doesn't matter who you are,
 if you are a complete stranger you can go into any house and sit down and they'd give you a cup of tea and home-baked scones and that sort of thing. They still do that, in most parts of the Highlands, anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, they did, because if they had a piano everybody got round the piano and sang and sometimes danced in the house. I can very well remember them taking the poker and the tongs and doing the Sword Dance in my house when 
my father was alive, I can remember that. I suppose this was a party occasion, probably the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 Halloween}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 party that I mentioned before, but I just remember now seeing them dancing, but they'd no swords so they did it with the long poker and tongs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Many p
eople divide society into different social classes or groups - this is the period before 1918 - did you think of people belonging to one group and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think that the average British person ever became class conscious until the fi
rst socialist government got in. I think they are the people that brought in class more than anybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That would be ... the first socialist government was in about 19-- ... oh, what would it be? There wasn't a socialist 
government but there were socialists in the House of Commons about 1910 and 1911, and I think, myself, that this was the beginning of class consciousness. You know, the Tolpuddle Martyrs, well, I think the Industrial Revolution of 1846, this made a tremen
d
ous difference to the cities in Scotland, and in London, too, because in Cheapside the ladies of the city used to go out shopping with their shopping baskets and buy their lace and buy all sorts of things in the city markets. Now, after the Industrial Rev
o
lution sanitation was brought in and people became more conscious of litter. When I say 'litter' I don't mean in the sense that this litter is, but everything was thrown out on the street, all the garbage - there was no dustmen or anything like that. And 
t
his applied to London as well as every other city in Great Britain. But class consciousness, I don't think ... this was less noticeable in Scotland, I think, than any place else because, even if you lived in a country district where there was a large esta
t
e and one landowner, he was very kind as a rule to the people that worked for him, and he respected them and they respected him. But there was never any feeling of 'the boss' or 'the master' or anything like that, you know, they were very polite to their 
e
mployers. And they got very little money but they considered themselves very well off, because usually people that worked on an estate like that, they got perks, such as vegetables and eggs and milk and all sorts of things. They were very well off in comp
arison to the poor in a city.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So it was only after 1910, really, that people ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, it was really, I think, ... the main feeling about classes came in after the First World War.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 After that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, after the first World War. Prior to
 that we were in a sort of ... what shall I say? ... in a state of great enjoyment and pleasure for very many, and great poverty for others. There were very poor people everywhere, and of course, you'll never get away from there being poor people. The poo
r
 will always be with us, whether it's their own choosing or not. Some of the poor make a better go of life today than others and it was always the way. There was a lot of beggars about, always. And there was a lot of Italian hurdy-gurdy men with an organ 
a
nd a monkey to it. I can remember seeing those on the street when I was quite a small girl. And I remember the ice cream men, they used to call out 'hokey-pokey, penny a lump' and go about with their shining brass container on a cart that they pushed. The
y pushed it. They didn't have any horses or anything, there was no motorcars in these days. Transport has become ... oh, entirely different now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would people like that, tramps and beggars, be thought of as different groups or different classes from the working man, or from landowners?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I don't think so because as I told you, in my early days I remember the beggars coming round the door and they always got, in the wintertime a bowl of soup, and in the morning if they were there they got a bowl of po
rridge. But people were kind to them. But there was a lot of vagrants; always has been. And later on, you know, the workhouses, they used to take them in for a night and they could go into a workhouse at Leytonstone, perhaps, and then go to the next workh
ouse which might be at either Chingford or Epping or somewhere like that, and they would get a free night's bed and a wash, for one night only, and their breakfast. And they could go on roaming round the country like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 But they'd have to get quite a long way each day from one workhouse over to the next.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, but then they'd nothing else to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you think some groups of people felt superior to other groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I haven't known any of them that felt superior. The people that I've kn
ow that have been superior, they never make you feel inferior. Never. If you meet the Queen she doesn't make you feel inferior to herself. Not at all. She's just a natural ... nice woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Looking at yourself when you came to London, which is in this p
eriod again, you were doing a sort of job which wasn't usual for a woman to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Some people might have felt that you were in a different class or a different category from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, class never entered into it. Class never cam
e into it at all. There was no such thing as class, not that I ever remember. I never remember people talking about ... you know, one lot of people being better than another. I know it was the ambition of every mother in Scotland to have a son that was a 
minister. And in England the ambition of every mother was to have a son a banker. Then there was ... you know, men were very poorly paid and the soldiers only had a shilling a day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 After the War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, in the War, they only had a shilling a day. A
nd people were not well off but then, everything was very cheap. Do you know that you could buy a nice pair of boots for yourself for 4/11d. And you could buy a costume for 12/11, or 12/11 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs18 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs18\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 3/4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 d. There was always three-farthings on everything. And if they h
adn't got a farthing they would give you a little sheet of pins instead of the farthing. But a blouse ... you could go to Bourne }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 Hollingsworth and buy a beautiful blouse for 2/11d. And they had nothing else in these days but blouses and ribbons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At Bourne }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  Hollingsworth?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 At Bourne }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 Hollingsworth. They had one window with blouses and another window with ribbons, and that was all they had. And I remember getting beautiful blouses there, beautifully embroidered blouses for 2/11d. You could buy a
 hat for 2/11, and milliners ... every other shop you came to was a hat shop. Everybody wore hats, it didn't matter whether you were a child or grown up, you wore a hat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I like the idea of you getting a sheet of pins if they didn't have a farthing!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you ever told to curtsey to anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, when you were a little girl, you know, if you were brought in to see your mother's friends in the afternoon, you had to do a bob.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was there anyone you called 'sir' or 'master'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In the area where you lived who was considered to be the most important person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I knew nobody that was considered to be important. Nobody. Not one person that was more important than any of the others. Not as far as I knew. Your teacher put the fear of death in your of course. Your schoolteacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So they were regarded as quite important? And Clergymen, what about them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, we used to see clergymen in and out of the house, but nobody made anything ... They weren't sor
t of treated as if they were gods, or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What about the landowner in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, he went about with the rest of ... everybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Who did people tend to associate with? Did they associate with people in the same sort of jobs as themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
If you can picture for one single minute the Hebrides, or the Highlands or any place, even Devonshire or Cornwall, or any of these places, I can't see how they could differentiate between people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Because they are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 sparsely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  populated, do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, even in Devonshire and in Cornwall and in Gloucestershire and all these places, there are still landlords and as far as I know - and the ones that I have met - there has never been any 'side', what you would call side, or no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 pretensions}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 . They don't need to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 pretend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 . They're just gentlemen or ladies, and that's that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Everybody is a gentleman or a lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. And this is true for the Highlands of Scotland because they say that every person there, they're born ladi
es and gentlemen. So they say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would this apply to Glasgow as well, do you think, or not so much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, so far as I know when I was young and in Glasgow, I never knew anything about class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where you lived did people have similar standards of living, or would you say that different groups had different standards of living?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Is this in Scotland or in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Either, whichever ... Well, both, then. What can you remember in Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, the people that my aunt and my uncle
 associated with were just people like themselves. And in London here, after I came to London I very well remember seeing Harry and 'Arriet going out. The woman would have a great big feather in her hat, and they used to go out every Sunday, and they woul
d
 have a little trap and horse and maybe go to Abridge, where you were today, for the afternoon. And they always dressed themselves up on Sundays, and on Saturdays. And you would see them dancing outside the public houses in London where you'd never see th
a
t in Scotland. But you would see that in London. And they would have the children outside the pub door while they were inside, drinking, I suppose. But I never saw ... it was a very unusual thing to see anybody drunk in London, but a very usual thing in t
h
e City of Glasgow to see people drunk. There was a vast difference between the two countries because in England here most people are beer drinkers. In Scotland they're whisky drinkers. Whisky and beer. And I think, myself, that you see more drunken men, s
a
y, in the streets in Glasgow than you see in the streets of London, any time. I have noticed this very forcibly. And I remember, I was going to tell you about 1911 when I came to London, I remember my sister and her husband - and she had 2 children - and 
m
yself, we were invited out to tea to some friends of hers, and they were real Cockneys. And he had a very good ... the husband had a very good business, I suppose they'd call in transport today, but it was all lorries and horses that he hired out, and I r
emember they had a huge big yard and they had chickens and goats, I think, or something. And when we went in to tea in their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  the table was set with bread and butter and all sorts of things, and to my amazement everybody had a huge pin sticking in the cloth beside where you sat. You know, there was your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 tea plate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 and your tea knife, and then this huge pin, and I was perplexed to know what the pin was for. Do you know what it was for? For eating winkles. They had a great bowl of winkles on the tabl
e. Evidently this was a great cockney treat. A bowl of winkles, and you took off their little heads and then you ate the winkle. Of course, I'd never seen this in my life before. And they were very nice people, but real thoroughbred cockneys, there was no
 doubt about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And the pin was all laid ready?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
The pin was all ... sticking up, sticking in the cloth, standing up. A huge pin, mind you, about that size. They were proper winkle pins, I understand. I don't think you get them today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you think your mother thought of herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you remember anyone being described as 'a real gentleman' or 'a real lady'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, plenty of people. I know lots of people, and I know tha
t one always imagined oneself to be 'a real lady', or a gentleman, if you were a man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you know what the significance of that term was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think just decent manners, and decent to your fellow man, as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child? Thinking of Scotland, at the moment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, yes, I remember seeing a policeman and I remember seeing the superintendent of police because my uncle that I stayed with in Stornoway, he was a very keen fisher
man and he used to go out fishing and whatever he caught he always sent it out to his friends and I remember him sending me to the superintendent of police - this was in Stornoway - with some fish that he had caught. And I remember the superintendent of p
olice showing me the cells in the police station. Well, I'd be about 12 at that time, and of course, I had never been inside a police station in my life, so I saw these cells then. But strangely enough ... may I go away from this for a moment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I went to see over the newest police station in London at Holborn 3 or 4 years ago and I never saw such luxury in my life. I was shown all the drying rooms for the policemen's clothes, their car park and where they keep the horses and the informati
on room and enquiry room, and I was with the superintendent of police and I was taken up to his room and the Bristol Milk Sherry was brought out and I had a sherry, and then I went and saw over the whole of the police station, lovely lecture rooms - beaut
iful, and any amount of them, too - and a lovely }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 where you could get a nice lunch, which I had there. And then after lunch I was taken to see the cells, and this surprised me more than anything that has happened to me, I should think, to see thi
s place. They showed me a cell and there was a nice bed with a pillow, white pillowcase on it, and a blanket, in a room, and then there was a washbasin with hot and cold water, with a mirror and a towel, and a lavatory in a room when you came out of there
.
 And a bell in the cell so that the man who is in the cell, or a woman, can ring. And I said 'who do they ring for?' For the officer on duty, if they want anything they ring for him. I said 'well, Mr. Smith ... Superintendent Smith, the next time that I h
a
ve lost my train to Loughton I'm going to come in to your enquiry box and tell them that I've thrown a brick through a window, will they please lock me up for the night'. Really and truly you couldn't ... when I heard of ringing the bell for the officer! 
A beautiful place! And do you know, if Holloway's like this I'm not surprised that all the prisons are full up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Holloway isn't like that, I assure you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Why, what's it like, is it drab?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you were in Stornoway what was the people's attitude to a policeman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you ever threatened with the police if you were a naughty girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, no, no, no, nobody. ... You know, there's only been one murder committed in that island for over a hundred years. And sometimes ... you never lift the pa
per but you see somebody's be brought up for drunken driving, you see that. And there's no public bars anywhere, not a public house, but they've got bars, and you've to come maybe 27 miles to get a glass of beer which is very wrong because, if they had a 
bar in every village these people wouldn't come into the town to get tipsy, and this is what they do perhaps, on a Friday or a Saturday after they've had their pay, they come in to the nearest bar and sit and drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did people generally have a good relationship with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. There they did. Oh, no doubt about to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And what about in Glasgow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think in Glasgow, too. You know, the police were always highly respected until recently, until all these crowds of youngsters have got 
on the street, and these demonstrations. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 
I don't think there was ever a time that I know of in the history of Great Britain when policemen were as downtrodden as they are today, because the policeman's not allowed to use the rights of his professions. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You know, he's to be so careful that he doesn't do this to a prisoner or that to a prisoner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 To upset anybody. Do you remember feeling that your mother had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, after my father died, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did you think about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, I didn't know anything about it, it was only when I grew up that I realised. Mind you, we weren't as badly off as other people, but there was nothing for you then, so social security or anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was there the Poor Law in Scotland, did they have Guardians or the Parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, they had a poor house where people went if they had nowhere to stay, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was there any help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not help, unless you did something for yourself, you know, you worked or did something to e
arn your living. There was no help for anybody other than that. I don't think so. But I think there was some sort of form of a parochial board, that's what they called them in Scotland, and where people were destitute they would give help, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you given lessons by one of your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Or by a tutor or governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I went to school, a girls' school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old were you when you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I should think I was 7 or 8, or something, and I went to sc
hool in Glasgow. Then when I went up to Stornoway when I was 12 I went to the school called The Seminary, which I told you about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go to just those two schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I loved school, nearly broke my heart when I left it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you like it even when you went to the first one when you were 8?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, I was very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Is that the normal age for children to go to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, no. At that time, you see, we'd been moving from place to pl
ace and this interrupted my early schooling. I think the law for going to school when you were 6 or 7 came in much later than when I was at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And the first school, was that a girls' school or a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A girls' school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 They were both girls' schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Girls' schools, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Would these be Board schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no. Oh, no, they weren't. You had to pay a small fee, if I remember right, in both schools. They were both fee paying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go full time when you were 8?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, morning and afternoon. I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go home at lunchtime or did you have a meal ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, I went home at lunchtime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you feel about the teachers? at both of your schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I was very happy with my teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they emphasise certain things as important in life: manners, or tidiness, or punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, you were supposed to learn that at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If you did something that they disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, you'd be severely spoken to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Is that all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 As far as I know it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any gangs or groups or cliques in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And then after that you went to the college, didn't you, until you were 19?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Then we talked about you starting your job. There was one question that I lef
t out then. Did you belong to any trade union or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, good heavens, there wasn't such a thing as trade unions!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No professional organisation at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When you were working did your leisure activities and your home life change very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, well, up to a certain point it did because when I was working in London, you see, we had Saturday afternoon off. But everybody had to work on Saturday mornings. They worked every day except Sunday. They worked on Sa
turday mornings, but the shops, a lot of the shops were open on Saturdays until 11 o'clock at night. There was no early closing in these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you still have to keep up going to Church? Was it expected that you would still go to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well
, it was expected of you and I know, myself, that I ... when I was at college I used to go ... one of the main things that you could do on a Sunday was go to listen to tiptop preachers, and one learned a lot. And, of course, I belonged to a debating socie
ty, a literary debating society, T.P. O'Connors, I used to read his things. And I belonged to The Women's Social }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 Political Union. I belonged to that. That was the beginning of the suffragettes. They were the non-militant ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 This was in Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, in Glasgow, when I was at college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you tell me anything about this, because I don't suppose we'll meet anybody else who was a member.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, it just so happened that at the time of the votes for women there was great demonstrations 
going on all over Great Britain at that time to get votes for women. And the Women's Social }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 Political Union was a body that women could join when they were 18 years of age and learn about political life and industry and interesting things. But there was 
no ... they didn't throw themselves under horses, or anything like that, they were non-militant, but they were part of the suffragette movement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you were active in this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. Oh, yes. Oh, yes, I was. I was sent out to work in the slums.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 To get other women interested in this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, but to see how other people lived. This is one of the things you had to do. And then, when there was an election you were sent out to canvass for the member of parliament, for some member of parliament
. We rang the doors, and that sort of thing, collecting support for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you belong to this when you came to London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you vote in the first election when women could vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What party did you vote for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Conservative Party. Never been anything else in my life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your husband vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He was interested in politics, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, but not as interested as I was because he was away at sea so much, but he always voted when he was here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you or your husband ever feel under any pressure from anybody to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you an active member of the Party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And did your work for it at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your husband, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Well, he was away. But I always worked for the candidate, whoever was the candidate wherever I was. Churchill was our Member here, and I worked for him. I've got a lovely letter there from him. In the Women's Social }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14501719 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  Political Union, of
 course, this got me interested in politics. And my father was a Tory, and there are not very many Tories in Scotland, not to this day. Scotland was mostly Liberal, very strong Liberal, and when I was young I was sent to visit poverty-stricken slums in Gl
a
sgow, and they were dreadful, indeed, and then I became more politically inclined, and when the candidate was standing I went and helped the candidate, in 1910, and I've worked at every election since 1910 and this is the first one that I haven't worked i
n
, except one when I was out in India and there was an election then. But I've always helped the candidate. Always. I speak at meetings and I've acted as agent, where the agent ran away with a woman and I was left holding the baby and I held the baby succe
s
sfully and got my member into Parliament, which I was very proud and very pleased, and so was he. And he made a dinner and I was the guest of honour at this dinner at the House of Commons. But nothing will budge me from being a Conservative because I thin
k
, myself, that they have more ... they're less inclined to make people class conscious than the Socialists are. And trade unionism, you know, when it started in its very early days it was very much needed, because they needed trades unions. But the trades
 
unions have forgotten their place altogether because truthfully speaking we have no government in this country, we are governed by the trades unions. What I mean, they have strikes, they have all these things and the Government have very often to give int
o
 them for the sake of the country, and this is a bad thing. But I, myself, as I've said already, I've always been Conservative, and I remember very well at the time of the split between Asquith and Lloyd George, and the first Socialists getting in to Parl
i
ament and I've met many of them and I've many friends that are socialists, not ... I don't mean Labour, I mean Socialists, real Socialists. And the greatest Socialist when socialism was first talked of, there was 3 people that were outstanding in this mov
e
ment, that was Keir Hardie, Robert Blatchford and a woman called Mary Macarthur, and these people worked very hard to try and emancipate the working man. And this is in the period when trades unionism was beginning to be formed and the trades unions were 
v
ery badly needed. But since they've become political they have changed their aspect altogether because it's them that's keeping the Labour Party in power and the Labour Party - they call themselves the Labour Party, not because they labour, because they d
o
 not labour. They have a very easy time. But it caught on with the working people, this Labour business. When I've been canvassing at doors I've heard people, this Labour business. When I've been canvassing at doors I've heard people say to me, 'I'm Labou
r, I 'have to work for me living. I'm a labourer and I vote Labour'. I can remember this quite well. But I've done a lot of political work and I went all over the Midlands and Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Bristol.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You told me once another reason for yo
ur views as a Conservative; because of the Conservative's ability to manage money or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, well, from a financial point of view there's no doubt about it that the majority of ... I wouldn't say the majority of Conservatives becaus
e there are plenty of Conservatives that are very poor, but a great deal of the business life of the country is financed by people ... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 moneyed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  people who invest money in businesses and who have, perhaps, a bigger share of the wealth of the country than oth
ers. They may have got it with their own powers, or inherited it, but they do invest it, and I feel, myself, that a Conservative government from the point of view of bringing the country out of the depths it has fallen into now will be better for us, from
 
that point of view. I'm quite sure that it will give people at home and abroad more confidence in us. You see, when people never have had anything ... people that have never had anything, are inclined to abuse it, but people who always have had most of th
e
 things of life, they never abuse anything. There's no reason for them to abuse it. Mind you, there are lots of people who have very little in life, nice people who have very little in life - and today this is particularly true of elderly people who have 
n
o pensions or anything else - and they've got a pretty rough time, but the British working man hasn't got a rough time, nor the British working woman today, because they're all earning and they're spending as fast as they're earning. They're not saving on
e
 single farthing today, because they know they can get social security benefits if anything befalls them and they haven't got the independence of spirit that one would expect them to have, because I would think that it's the last thing on earth to have to
 
go for assistance, public assistance. Now, people have been brought up with a changed attitude altogether. They've been brought up with the idea that if they're in need the State will help them. Well, the poor old State has been helping so many people and
 helping so many countries abroad that it hasn't got much left. I don't know what you think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 After you left school, and training, how did you spend your time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, I belonged to an amateur operatic society; I belonged to a choir; I belonged to a 
debating society and I belonged to a rambling club. Is that enough for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, thank you (laughter) Did you make many new friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, lots of friends, men and women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever bring them home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she expect to know where you went, and did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not after I grew up. Until I was about 20 I think my mother would be very distressed if I was going anywhere and I 
didn't tell her where I was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You started to be very interested in Gaelic culture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 After I came to London. Not in Scotland. It's a strange thing, that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was this before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, it was. And it started in Glasgow now I come to th
ink of it, that a friend ... you know, I told you, I stayed with an aunt and she had a daughter and this daughter had a friend, and strangely enough I met her in Glasgow about 1911, I think, and I haven't seen her for a number of years. And she invited me
 
to her house and there I met a friend of hers who belonged to a Gaelic choir in Glasgow. And we were at a party and I had to sing and she said 'oh, you must join the choir'. So I joined the choir and that was the beginning of me taking an interest in Gael
ic because really I didn't know that there was such a language. Although I'd been up in Stornoway I hardly knew anything about Gaelic because my own people that I stayed with spoke English, fluently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And that was how it began?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That was how it began.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And when you come to London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
When I came to London, of course, I was only here for a short time when War broke out, and I went to a Gaelic choir concert in London with a gentleman friend of my brother-in-law's, and this started me getting in
terested in Gaelic in London. And the conductor of the Gaelic choir told me that they were having a dance the following Saturday, or something in the Furnival Hall - that's in Holborn - and would I like to come. And of course, this friend was a cousin of 
hers and he said 'oh, yes, we'll come along', and they took me there. And then she said to me that there was a Gaelic Society in London and I ought to join, and I did join the Gaelic Society in London at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you've run it ever since?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 W
ell, I've been in it ever since. I've been everything in it. I haven't got my watch on now, but they presented me with a beautiful gold watch and a book of autographs, and this record ... what do you call it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Radio?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Radio, they presented me wit
h that, and a book with the autographs of every member of the society in it, and it's quite interesting too, and an illuminated address in the front.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was your husband interested in it, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He worked for it, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, yes. And I used to have the whole choir down in my house, you know, for 'bring-and-buy' sales, and all the money that they raised was to take them to musical festivals in Scotland. And I was secretary of that, too, later on, and vice president. An
d I'm still vice president.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What age were you when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Twenty-seven and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long had you known your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 About 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4213195  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 We met in my sister's house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
He came from Cheshire, but he was born, strangely enough, in Stornoway. His mother went for ... her husband was at sea and his mother went for a holiday up there. She came from that part. She went for a holiday and he was born before they expected him,
 so he was very proud of the fact that he was born in Stornoway and he was really a Highlander, but he couldn't speak Gaelic. And I was born in the Lowlands, but all my blood was Highland, of course, but I could even speak Gaelic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you save up money before getting married, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
I never wanted to get married. No, the last thing in the world I ever wanted to do. I had a very good profession and I was very anxious to have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 bachelor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  flat in London, and the only thing that I had towards it when
 I got engaged was a cigarette box, and I don't smoke (laughter). No, I never wanted to get married I wanted to have a career and be a career woman, but I never regretted getting married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What made you change your mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, I met the right man, that's why. And a very good man he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your mother help you in setting up home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long were you engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Nine months. My husband sent me instructions ... his ship got torpedoed in the Channel ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He sent you a message saying that you should be ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Ah, that was after. We'll have to go back a little bit. We got engaged and my husband went to sea and this was during the First World War and things were not as bad as they were in the second War, of course, they 
wasn't the bombing, and there were one or two zeppelins game over, and tales about the Russians walking ... tramping through London, which was pure rubbish. But when I got engaged to my husband he went away and he was coming back, he thought he'd be back 
in December and we fixed our wedding for December 23}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 rd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
, and we had to wire everybody and cancel the wedding because there was no husband. He hadn't turned up and we had to eat our wedding breakfast on Christmas Day. I well remember this and I was very distr
essed about it, and everything ready except the man and he didn't come. And I've always teased him and said he'd got torpedoed so that he wouldn't have to come to the wedding (laughter). He got torpedoed in the Channel, on the way home, and for weeks I di
d
n't know if he was living or dead and it was a very worrying time indeed. And then I had a scribbled note that was very smudged and looked as if it had been in dozens of hands, and it was. It went from torpedo boat to torpedo boat and took about 3 or 4 we
e
ks to come, to say that "all's well, love Norman". That was all that was in it. And eventually after they'd managed to run this ship, it didn't sink, and he was Chief Engineer of the ship, and the chief engineer and the captain have always to stand by whi
l
e the funnel is above water, and they were in a destroyer. And all the rest of the crew were sent to Dunkirk. Mind you, he had been to Gravesend and let the troops off his ship and all the passengers. Got as far as Gravesend when the Government sent him b
a
ck to France ... sent the ship back with all the food, 300,000 lambs and butter and everything, food for the troops. And on their way over, as New Year was coming in, they got torpedoed. But the ship didn't sink and they stood by in a destroyer for 3 days
 
and my husband and the captain were there, and my husband decided that he would go on board and try ... get one of the engineers to come from the hotel where they were staying and go into the engine room and see if they could light a boiler and run the sh
i
p onto the sands at Dunkirk. And he went into the boiler room and was up to his neck, and my husband was 6'3". And he managed to light a boiler and to run the ship onto the sands at Dunkirk. They had to unload all the lambs and put them floating in the Ch
a
nnel, and all the food that was on board had to be thrown overboard so that they could save the ship. And it took 3 months, nearly, for them to get back to London, and we just managed to save the 3 months that you're allowed when your banns go up, to get 
m
arried without having them called again. So, if that wasn't a catastrophe! But during the time he was over there, I had, of course, given in my resignation and left the firm because I was expecting to get married in December, and while my husband was over
 with his ship and I was in London, here, twiddling my fingers he wrote me and told me ... Mind, you, I had ... Before when I was going to get married we had agreed that I'd find a house and I'd found a very nice house with 4 bedrooms, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 , a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 drawing room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 , a kitchen and a scullery, a nice garden and a conservatory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
In Leytonstone which was a very nice part in these days, every house had its servants then. But I had this house, you see, so my husband wrote me a letter and 
he said to keep me busy he thought the best thing I could do was to go and buy everything I wanted for the house. Just like that. So, as I told you I was an auditor and I did all sorts of firms and this firm, they were manufacturers of furniture and I wen
t to them and I got everything at manufacturer's cost price, which was very nice, and you'd be amazed to see I've still got the bills here, everything that I bought.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And still some of the furniture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Everything that I required in the house, excep
t one thing. When I got engaged to my husband I told him I'd never mind anything I did in the house but I'd never wash clothes, I hated washing. I hate it to this day. But I bought everything for my house. I went to this furniture place with my sister and
 one of the managers - he was a director, really - he said, 'now tell me how much furniture you want, what rooms do you want? Have you got any ideas about it?' And I said, 'yes, I'd like to have Queen Anne things for my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 ', reproduction, of course, 'and Jacobean for my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
, and four bedrooms and a kitchen'. He said, 'well, we can do everything for you but kitchen furniture because we've had to give everything up for the troops, wooden tables and chairs, we've had to give them all up'. So he
 said 'the rest you can have here'. And do you know, we bought everything for the house in 2 hours, and we thought it was going to take a long time. But we had to go to other places to get carpets and linen and glass and everything I required. My cutlery 
and everything that's in there is all what I started with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you did that in the 3 months when your husband ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I didn't, I did it in one afternoon, most of it. And then I went up another day where I got all my china and glass, and I dre
w designs for my tea service, and saw a dinner service I liked. And I got everything, a breakfast service ... everything I wanted. Coffee service, everything I wanted. Bought the whole lot. I went the whole hog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Had you given up work by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh
, I was at home all the time. I bought everything I required in the house, but one thing and it was the first thing that I ever did require in my house. I told you I hated washing and I told my husband. And my husband said, 'well, you can send anything yo
u
 like to the laundry', and that was that. But when I furnished the house I had to go over every day and give it a flick round with a duster and see that everything was right, and open the windows and the doors for a bit, and so forth, because he hadn't co
m
e home yet. And I had some friends ... a friend who was a rubber planter out in Malaya and he and his wife came to stay with us for a weekend and I never missed a day without going over to the house. And this weekend I missed because we went up to town to
 
dinner and we went to a theatre. And when I went over on Monday the water was cascading down on top of the lovely carpets and the furniture. A pipe had burst and I hadn't turned off the water. I didn't know you had to turn off water, and everything was so
a
king. However, the gentleman next door had realised that the pipes had burst and he broke the scullery window and come in and turned off the water. And when I got there on the Monday the first thing that I required was a rope and pegs, the two things I'd 
n
ever bought. A clothes rope and pegs. But the want of a clothes rope and pegs had a very regarding result because I went to my neighbours, two neighbours, and they became life-long friends of ours while they lived. And they took my carpets and put them ov
e
r the lines in their gardens and we got it dry somehow. But what with having a husband torpedoed and the house torpedoed, too. Water!! I love the sea, but by Jove, the rain did more damage than ever the sea did! (laughter) And this is perfectly true. But 
eventually we got it all dried and everything was very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you still living with your sister and your mother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. Not with my mother, my sister. My mother had gone back to Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Had she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. And she died in Scotl
and, as a matter of fact, years afterwards, of course. But it was a very funny things about the clothes ropes. The only thing that I wouldn't have and that's the thing I needed most. I had everything else that you could thing of. Everything; cutlery, cook
ing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 utensils}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 , and I've got them all to this day. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 settee}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  you're sitting on now, that was in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 drawing room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
, and the piano of course, I gave to the hospital where my husband died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Can you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. It was a very smart Naval wedding, all the officers on the ship came. My goodness, I had a photograph of it somewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where was the wedding? You had a large wedding from your sister's house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have lots of presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, a lot of presents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not for 6 weeks, because my husband ... his ship had just come in, you see, and he had to be on the ship before he could get his holiday.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long did you live at the house in Leytonstone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 The first house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Thirteen years. Then I lived for 12 years in another house in Leytonstone. And then I lived another 28 years in Loughton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How old was your husband when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He was 37.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was he a permanent ... in the Royal Navy? He hadn't just joined because of the ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
All the ships were taken over by the Royal Navy during the War, you know. They were taken over. He was in the Merchant service, a Chief Engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I see, and then it was taken over by the Royal Navy. Had he always been a sailor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Or did he have any other jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And did he continue?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. When I met him he was the youngest chief engineer sailing into London, in a big ship, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And did he continue in the Royal Navy 'till he retired?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did your husband feel about you working after your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never! That was never, never allowed. No self-respecting man would let his wife work, in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, well, I would have been quite happy to have carried on with my career, but I couldn't have, it wouldn't have worked out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your husband enjoy his career?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, very much. Oh, yes. Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have any children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, two, a son and a daughter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were they born before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 One of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That was Donald?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When was he born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He was born at the end of 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was he born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. And I may tell you that I had a very difficult time with my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 ba
bies, when}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 they were born and during the ... there was 3 doctors there and a nurse to bring this child into the world and during the delivery there was a knock on the bell downstairs. We were showing a light from the bedroom window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Wartime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Wartime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your husband help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 In what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 With the birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You had a nurse, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long did you have to stay in bed for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A month at that time. Everybody had to stay a month in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did any of your relations or neighbours help?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, no, I had a servant. No, no, I had a domestic servant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long did you have the nurse for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How did you feed your first baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 To begin with I breast fed him and then I took ill and he had to go on artificial food, on Glaxo, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If you needed advice whom did you ask? About looking after babies, or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I went by what the doctor told me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If the baby was asleep would you wake it for a feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, he was fed at regular times. I never had to feed them through the night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If he cried before the normal time would you feed him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think so. My doctor taught me to bring them up by the clock: put t
hem to bed at a regular time, feed them at a regular time, and I never had any trouble with my children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When did you give it solid food first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, not 'till they were about 7 months old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When did you wean the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When they were abo
ut 9 months, but I had to wean the baby ... my first baby, and the second one I never breast fed at all ... but I had to wean him at 3 months because I took ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you wean him suddenly or gradually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I think it had to be gradually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I can't remember, I was very ill at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you think at the time that it did any harm to a baby to let it cry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Never thought of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How much did your husband have to do with your children when they were babies under a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you know what your husband earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you discuss together how the money should be spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 He gave me everything he had and he never asked me where I put a penny. Immediately we were married an account
 was open in the bank and we never had a separate purse. Mark you, I will say that I never was extravagant and I always spent wisely, got good food, good clothes and I didn't need to do anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 How long did you have your pair help in the house for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, 'till the children were about 12.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did the girl call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did she wear a uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 She wasn't a girl. Two of them were older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You had one at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 One at a time, a housekeeper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Where did she sleep and eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, she had her own bedroom and she ate in the kitchen, and sat in the kitchen, too. But she was quite comfortable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you supervise all the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, in a sort of way. Two of my maids, they were excellent women. Ex
cellent. Couldn't be better. One of them, she was a Yorkshire woman and she even boiled the scouring cloth on the washing day. She was so clean. Spotlessly clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you give them any moral guidance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, I don't think so because they were both older than me. They could have given me moral guidance, perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were they allowed any time to do just what they liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, they had their days off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And could they go out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, yes. Absolutely free. They had the freedom of the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they do all the housework and the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Most of it. Of course, mind you, I helped, myself. I did the ironing and I helped with the cooking if they would allow me to. Sometimes ... one of them, oh, she liked to do everything herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were either of them responsible for the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, unless I was out. If I was out they would be. But I always bathed my children myself, every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did your children call them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 One was called Kate and the other one was called Mrs. Day. She was always called 'Mrs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did they call the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, Donald and Margaret.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you mend clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did your husband help with anything in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Decorating, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No. He wasn't domesticated at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did he read to the children or tell them stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, he'd tell them stories, he was very fond of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did the children have any regular household tasks to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What time did they go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Very early when they were babies, they went ... started bathing them at half past 5 and went to bed at 6 o'clock. And when my son was 14 I insisted on him being in bed before 10 o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What did you cook on, range or gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 A gas stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You said you made all your own jam and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you grow your own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Some of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you keep any livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, talk about livestock. When the children were about 10 and 12, I think they would be, we had a canary, a cat, 2 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 guinea pigs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 , 6 dogs and 2 children to feed. (laughter) That's the livestock!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Who looked after all these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Who do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, of course! Everybody when they got new animals: 'oh, we'll look after them', but they never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were the children allowed to talk during meals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well a normal sort of conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 What was your attitude if they left something uneaten on their plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I never said 'if you don't eat your porridge you'll get it for dinner', I never said }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\ul\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  to them! No, they were very good, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they have to hold their knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, from a very early age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did all the family present for a meal sit down together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. All that was present and that was myself most of the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When your children were young did you feel that there was a right way or a wrong way of bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, definitely. A right way, to tell the truth, be honest, and be decent to other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you and your husband have the same sort of ideas about bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, we never discussed them. I brought them up. He was away most of the time. But he was very upright himself. I never knew my husban
d to tell a lie, or swear. Never say a swear word and he was known to be the only engineer sailing into London that didn't swear. He'd a reputation for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 That's some reputation. Was your mother alive when your children were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you see much of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Not not after I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Was your mother-in-law near?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No, she was up in Cheshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you let your children join in when grownups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Join in the conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 I don't think they would ever be interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were you able to leave the children when they were young so that you could both go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Only when I had help in the house. I'd never leave them alone. I never left them alone, until they were old enough t
o look after themselves, 15 or 16.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there any other children you discouraged them from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If they did something you disapproved of what would happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, I used to tell them ... I used to tell Donald that when }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 Daddy}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  came home he'd give him the slipper, if he did anything. But he was a good boy. They were good children, really, I had no bother bringing them up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When your children had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes. They had birthday parties and I made ice cream for them myself, and they had all their little friends in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have any musical instruments? Oh, you said you had your piano then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, both of them were taught.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were they taken shopping and visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes, they went wherever I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did they ever go out with just their father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, sometimes, but that was ... well, when he'd be at home he take them out. And if we had visitors, sometimes the visitors
 would take them out, and I remember a very interesting incident, just for the moment it's come to me. When my daughter was about 6 I had an uncle and aunt of mine came to stay with us and they took the 2 children up the road, in Leytonstone. My uncle was
 
a very tall man and they took them into a shop, a toy shop, and he thought of buying them a ball or something. He asked Donald what he would like, and Donald told him what he would like and he got it. Then he asked Margaret what she'd like and she put her
 
eyes up to the shelf at the top of the shop, 'I'd like that doll's house'. And my uncle said, 'oh, well, that's a very big thing to carry home, would you like a ball?' 'No, I'd like that doll's house'. And no matter what he offered her in the shop she wou
l
d have nothing but the doll's house, and home they came with the doll's house. And they had pleasure out of it! Both of them! Well, Margaret, she wouldn't have been more than 3 1/2 or something like that, and Donald about 6 and they both played with this,
 
and every time we went out we'd to buy more furniture for the doll's house, you know, those miniature things, and make curtains. And, oh, they cleaned the windows and they cleaned the floor and it gave them years of pleasure. They were very happy children
 
and played with a lot of toys that didn't cost very much. Do you know that I remember my son .. he had a teddy bear and he wouldn't go to sleep without his teddy bear. And all the wool got worn off the teddy bear and he lost his eyes and we put buttons on
 
for his eyes. And later on my son ... I remember once going in and seeing them with dolls that he had made ... a doll that Margaret had lost ... one doll had lost it's hair, another doll had lost its eyes, and Donald took the two dolls to pieces and made 
one doll - put the hair of one doll onto the other, and he called it The Dolls' Restoration Home. And do you know, this was when he was only 10.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Doctors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, and put the arms and the legs, put them all on. And then they started making what they 
called 'bubbies' and they made out of cloth - Donald, mostly - with buttons from the button box and bits of cloth, made a whole lot of children, and had a little school and put all the children in a row, some little 'bubbies' and some big 'bubbies', and p
ut them all in a row, teaching them at school. They made their own pleasures.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Amazing, as young as that!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes. And they were very happy. They always played together. Wherever the one was the other was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 All of you, when you husband was home, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 If he was at home he came with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes, we used to take a house at Birchington, in Kent and it was beautiful. And the maid used to come with us. And I remem
ber being there for 30 days and not a drop of rain! Brilliant sunshine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Were there books, newspapers, magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you belong to a library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you read aloud to the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 When they were little, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you spend Sundays any differently from those you'd spent as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11342366\charrsid4213195 Not really, not as strict as I was brought up. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Not as strictly as I was brought up, but I always made the children go to Sunday School and I went to Church, myself. And we had visitors on a Sunday, and children sometimes came to tea. We didn't make any difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And you continued all your activities with ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Well, they accumulated from one to another, I don't know. I started a club with other ... four
 friends, for young Scots in London and we managed to get a church hall at Edgware Road. We started this in 1923, the year of the Wembley Exhibition, I think it was, or the year after the Wembley Exhibition. 1923 or '24. However, we started this club - a 
s
ocial club - for lonely Scots in London and they paid 3/-d. I think, to become a member and I used to bake every Monday 300 scones and pancakes and take them up for tea at night. And always I made a provision that the maid would allow me to have the kitch
e
n to myself for that day. And I used to go out at 3 o'clock in the afternoon and get back at 11 o'clock at night. Mind you, the children were at this time 8 and 10, something like that, or 7 and 9, or something. And we had 700 members of that club. And I 
organised dances and supper dances and various things, and we made enough money to collect }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
6,000 to buy premises. And, of course, the War came, but this money was put on trust to buy premises, and we'd never be able to buy premises in London at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 6,000, so the interest of the money pays for the hall where they meet once a week now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you've been involved in all this for years and years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 All my life. All my life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you go to a lot of theatres and concerts and things at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 And the Gaelic Society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Oh, yes. And we arranged a ... for the Scottish Home Industries in Edinburgh we arranged a display of tweed-making at the Wembley Exhibition, and the Duke and Duchess of York, who later became King George VI and Que
en Elizabeth, came to this demonstration. And I left home with a 3-legged pan, with a girdle, you know, for making scones and a baking board and a rolling pin and I don't know what, rugs and everything else, and got a train to Liverpool St., changed there
 and got on to Baker Street and from Baker St. got on to Wembley. How I ever carried the stuff I don't know, but I got it there and I got it home and I've still got the girdle now. And we made }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14501719 \'a3}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 100 for the Scottish home industries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 So you had as busy a life then as you do now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Oh, busier than I have now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you have much time for just you and your husband to go to things together when he was at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7351819\charrsid4213195 Aye,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195  wherever I went, he went or wherever he went I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 You did it all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
Yes, yes. And I had no outside activities that he didn't know of and he knew all my friends and they all knew him, all his life. And I still have friends in London today that I had then. Many of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4006042 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 Did you feel any more awareness of social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15676035 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
No, never. Never come in to my orbit at all. I think people make this themselves, and more so in a suburban town you hear of the Joneses and people like that, but I have never found this the case. Never. And I've got lots of friends that are i
n very high places, perhaps people would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7351819\charrsid4213195 think,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887223\charrsid4213195 
 but they're just the same as me and I'm just the same as them. They never make me feel inferior, never.
